They have the same powers and skills as a normal paladin.. except their rotten to the core  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ufalzure.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Falzure</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/2/02 1:33:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=477.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: In other words</span><hr size=1> The problem with &quot;fallen paladins&quot; is that a paladins power is still devine in origin, and should he turn his back on his deity, then his deity would revoke said powers.<br>
<br>
Notice how shadow Knights powers are based on necromancy, which is magic based, not devine <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  .<br>
<br>
In AD&amp;D (which is what VI &quot;borrowed&quot; most of its material from) when a paladin fell in disfavor with his god/godess he would be stripped of his powers and become an equivalent level fighter(warrior) until he was once again in favor with his deity.<br>
<br>
So although there is no in-game system to repremand fallen paladins, for RP reasons you would be better off creating a Shadow Knight.<br>
<br>
just a thought or two<br>
<br>
